# Docker Desktop + WSL 2 Installation Guide (Windows)

**Author:** Swarnasree  
**Environment:**
- Windows 10/11
- WSL 2
- Ubuntu
- Docker Desktop 4.81.0
- Docker Engine 29.6.1

---

# Objective

Install Docker Desktop on Windows and use Docker commands directly from Ubuntu (WSL 2).

---

# Prerequisites

- Windows 10/11
- Administrator access
- Internet connection
- WSL 2 installed
- Ubuntu installed from Microsoft Store

---

# Step 1 - Verify WSL

Open **Command Prompt** or **PowerShell**

```powershell
wsl -l -v
```

Expected Output

```
NAME                   STATE           VERSION
* Ubuntu               Running         2
docker-desktop         Running         2
docker-desktop-data    Running         2
```

If Ubuntu is Version 1

```powershell
wsl --set-version Ubuntu 2
```

---

# Step 2 - Install Docker Desktop

Download Docker Desktop

https://www.docker.com/products/docker-desktop/

Install it.

During installation ensure

- Enable WSL 2 backend
- Install required WSL components

Restart the PC if prompted.

---

# Step 3 - Start Docker Desktop

Open Docker Desktop.

Wait until it shows

```
Engine running
```

---

# Step 4 - Enable WSL Integration

Open

```
Docker Desktop
    Settings
        Resources
            WSL Integration
```

Enable

- Enable integration with my default WSL distro
- Ubuntu

Click

```
Apply & Restart
```

---

# Step 5 - Restart WSL

Open Command Prompt

```powershell
wsl --shutdown
```

Open Ubuntu

```powershell
wsl
```

---

# Step 6 - Verify Docker in Windows

```cmd
docker version
```

Expected

```
Client:
Version: ...

Server:
Docker Desktop ...
```

Check running containers

```cmd
docker ps
```

Expected

```
CONTAINER ID   IMAGE   COMMAND   CREATED   STATUS   PORTS   NAMES
```

No containers is perfectly normal.

---

# Step 7 - Verify Docker in Ubuntu

Open Ubuntu

```bash
wsl
```

Run

```bash
docker version
```

Check running containers

```bash
docker ps
```

If you see container columns instead of an error, Docker integration is working.

---

# Step 8 - Test Docker

Run

```bash
docker run hello-world
```

Expected Output

```
Hello from Docker!
This message shows that your installation appears to be working correctly.
```

---

# Step 9 - Download an Image

```bash
docker pull nginx
```

List downloaded images

```bash
docker images
```

---

# Step 10 - Run Nginx Container

```bash
docker run -d --name mynginx -p 8080:80 nginx
```

Verify

```bash
docker ps
```

Open browser

```
http://localhost:8080
```

You should see

```
Welcome to nginx!
```

